["In trading and control-systems contexts, the term “hysteresis” implies a
 region or threshold where small oscillations don’t trigger action. It’s
  often used to reduce noise and prevent constant flipping back and forth.
   If you want a name that’s more intuitive or domain-specific than
 “hysteresis,” consider the following suggestions:\n\n1.
   **Price Buffer**  \n2. **Update Threshold**  \n3. **Deadband**
    \n4. **Stability Margin**  \n5. **Requote Threshold**  \n6. **Quote
     Tolerance**  \n7. **Slippage Guard**  \n8. **Requote Buffer**  \n9.
      **Gap Tolerance**  \n10. **Noise Filter**
  \n\nHere’s a bit of reasoning behind each name:\n\n- **Price Buffer**
   / **Requote Buffer**  \n  Emphasizes that this value acts as a
    “buffer zone” around price changes before the bot updates quotes.\n\n-
     **Update Threshold** / **Quote Tolerance** / **Gap Tolerance**  \n
      Directly conveys that there’s a certain threshold that must be
       exceeded before updating.\n\n- **Deadband**  \n  A classic
        control-systems term. It neatly describes a region where small
         changes do not trigger any action.\n\n- **Stability Margin**
          \n  Suggests that the bot is less jittery and more “stable”
           within this margin before adjusting orders.\n\n-
     **Slippage Guard** / **Noise Filter**  \n  More descriptive of the
      protective or filtering mechanism ensuring small price jitters don’t
       trigger updates.\n\nAny of these could replace “hysteresis” without
        losing the underlying meaning of a threshold or “band” around the
         market price that prevents frequent re-quotes."]},
